## 3. Bugs Encountered & Fixes

### Bug 1: GCS Deadlock on Relay Trigger

| | |
|---|---|
| **Symptom** | GCS froze completely when a drone hit the battery limit. Dashboard stopped updating. |
| **Root Cause** | `telemetry_poller()` held `fleet_lock` (a standard `threading.Lock()`) while calling `add_gcs_log()`, which also tried to acquire `fleet_lock`. Since `Lock()` is not reentrant, the thread deadlocked itself. |
| **Fix** | Changed `fleet_lock = threading.Lock()` → `fleet_lock = threading.RLock()` (reentrant lock). |
| **File** | [app.py](file:///home/ubuntu/githubrepos/dronesim/gcs/app.py) line 46 |

---

### Bug 2: "Working outside of application context" Crash

| | |
|---|---|
| **Symptom** | Relief drone upload succeeded, but `mission/start` crashed with `RuntimeError: Working outside of application context`. |
| **Root Cause** | The background `_execute_handoff()` thread called `_proxy_command()`, which used Flask's `jsonify()` to build return values. `jsonify()` requires an active Flask request context, which doesn't exist in background threads. |
| **Fix** | Replaced all `jsonify({...})` returns in `_proxy_command()` with raw Python dictionaries `{...}`. Flask auto-converts dicts to JSON in request handlers, and background threads simply ignore the return value. |
| **File** | [app.py](file:///home/ubuntu/githubrepos/dronesim/gcs/app.py) lines 275-307 |

---

### Bug 3: Docker Image Not Updating on Restart

| | |
|---|---|
| **Symptom** | After fixing Bug 2 in the source code and running `docker compose restart gcs`, the exact same error persisted. |
| **Root Cause** | The GCS Dockerfile copies `app.py` into the image at build time (`COPY gcs/ /app/`). A `restart` only stops/starts the existing container image — it does **not** re-copy updated source files. |
| **Fix** | Used `docker compose build gcs && docker compose up -d gcs` to rebuild the image with the latest source before restarting. |

---

### Bug 4: Relief Drone Holding Position Instead of Flying

| | |
|---|---|
| **Symptom** | Drone 2 (relief) received the mission and took off but immediately entered `HOLD` mode instead of flying the patrol. |
| **Root Cause** | `controller.py` duplicates waypoints ×50, so MAVSDK reports progress as e.g. `"15/100"`. The GCS was using `waypoints[15:]` on the base array (which only had 2 items), producing a single leftover waypoint — not enough for a patrol loop. |
| **Fix** | Used modulo arithmetic: `idx = current_wp % len(base_wps)`, then rotated the full base array to start from the correct position: `rem_wps = base_wps[idx:] + base_wps[:idx]`. This gives the relief drone a complete, correctly-rotated patrol loop. |
| **File** | [app.py](file:///home/ubuntu/githubrepos/dronesim/gcs/app.py) lines 152-158 |

---

### Bug 5: Relief Drone Battery Limit Mismatch

| | |
|---|---|
| **Symptom** | Drone 2 hit "low battery" only ~10 seconds after starting, instead of 150-180 seconds. |
| **Root Cause** | The user updated `start_mission()` to use `random.randint(150, 180)`, but `_execute_handoff()` still used the old `random.randint(50, 60)`. The relief drone inherited the short timer. |
| **Fix** | Synchronized `_execute_handoff()` to also use `random.randint(150, 180)`. |
| **File** | [app.py](file:///home/ubuntu/githubrepos/dronesim/gcs/app.py) line 318 |

